Currently, the EC GPIO list entry has an interrupt handler pointer for every entry.  This is wasteful, because most GPIOs don't have interrupt handlers.

So rather than have:

struct gpio_info {
	// ...Other fields...
	void (*irq_handler)(enum gpio_signal signal);
};

extern const struct gpio_info gpio_list[];

we could do:

struct gpio_info {
	// ...Other fields...
};

extern const struct gpio_info gpio_list[];
extern const void (*gpio_irq_handlers)(enum gpio_signal signal)[];

(and then a defined/enumerated constant for GPIO_INTERRUPT_COUNT)

On samus_pd, which is currently really low on space, there are 8 interrupt-capable GPIOs and 65 other GPIOs.  So this would save ~260 bytes of image size.

And thanks to robotboy's refactoring of the GPIO table to gpio.inc, this should be relatively straightforward to implement.

Current we calculate paint invalidation rects for the following purposes:

1. If the object has just been laid out (and if the object has not been marked full invalidation), we determine if an object needs paint invalidation by comparing previousPaintInvalidationRect and currentPaintInvalidationRect;

2. Detect movement by comparing the locations of previousPaintInvalidationRect and currentPaintInvalidationRect, as well as previousPositionFromPaintInvalidationBacking and currentPositionFromPaintInvalidationBacking. If there is movement, force full paint invalidation of all objects on the same backing in the whole subtree;

3. If the object is marked needing full invalidation, we invalidate the whole previousPaintInvalidationRect and currentPaintInvalidationRect on the backing; otherwise invalidate the diff on the backing.

Calculating the paint invalidation rects / positions
- is the main cost of the paint invalidation stage;
- still have many open bugs that are hard to resolve with the current architecture (e.g. bug 426114, bug 416539, bug 416535)

With slimming paint, we may
- no longer need to invalidate the rects on backing;
- have new ways to resolve the old bugs;
- still need to save previousPaintInvalidationRect and/or previousPosition, or something similar, to detect paint invalidation because of layout change, but perhaps with smaller cost to calculate them; 
- no longer need to full invalidate the whole subtree on object movement;
(please add anything I'm missing)

